Quite remarkably, all available ${{\mathrm J}/\psi}$ and $\Upsilon$ suppression measurements from fixed-target experiments (SPS, HERA, FNAL) to RHIC could be described within the above simple model on a broad kinematical range in rapidity $y$ (or ${x_{\mathrm{F}}}$)~\cite{Arleo:2012rs}.\footnote{A simple extension of the model {(\ref{{pheno-model}})} to double differential cross sections ${\rm d}\sigma^{\psi}_{\rm pA}/{{\rm d} {E}}{{\rm d}^2 \vec{p}_\perp}$ similarly yields a good description of the quarkonium suppression data as a function of transverse momentum~\cite{Arleo:2013zua}.} The predictions for ${{\mathrm J}/\psi}$ and $\Upsilon$ suppression in p--Pb collisions at $\sqrt{s}=5.02$~TeV~\cite{Arleo:2012rs} are shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:lhc}. As can be seen, the model predicts a rather strong ${{\mathrm J}/\psi}$ suppression at forward rapidity (say, $y\gtrsim3$) and a slight enhancement in the most backward rapidity bins ($y<-4$). The suppression predicted in the $\Upsilon$ channel shares the same features, however the suppression is less pronounced than that of ${{\mathrm J}/\psi}$, since the (average) coherent energy loss scales as ${M_\perp}^{-1}$, see Eq.~{(\ref{{coh-loss}})}. The latter predictions proved to be in excellent agreement with ALICE~\cite{Abelev:2013yxa} and LHCb~\cite{Aaij:2013zxa} data. 


